{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17633424","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17633424"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:53:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:53:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17478"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17478","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17478"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10168"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115224"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10168","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10168"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17478"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97233"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"7710"},{"type":"tags","id":"7721"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23770"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23786"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115224","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115224"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA researcher is analysing the distribution of serum creatinine values in a large population study. The data shows the following statistical properties:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMean: 85 \u00b5mol/L\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMedian: 75 \u00b5mol/L\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMode: 70 \u00b5mol/L\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESkewness: +1.5\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EKurtosis: 4.2\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the shape of this distribution?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Right-skewed with light tails","Left-skewed with heavy tails","Symmetrical with heavy tails","Left-skewed with light tails","Right-skewed with heavy tails"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe distribution is \u003Cstrong\u003Eright-skewed with heavy tails\u003C/strong\u003E. This can be determined from several features:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe mean (85) is greater than the median (75), which is greater than the mode (70) - a classic pattern of right skewness\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe positive skewness value (+1.5) confirms the right skew\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe kurtosis value of 4.2 is higher than that of a normal distribution (3.0), indicating heavy tails\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESkewness measures asymmetry in a distribution. A positive skewness indicates a longer right tail with the bulk of values on the left, while negative skewness indicates a longer left tail with the bulk of values on the right. A normal distribution has a skewness value of 0.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EKurtosis measures the tendency for a distribution to have extreme values or outliers. A normal distribution has a kurtosis value of 3 (often called mesokurtic). Values greater than 3 indicate heavy tails (leptokurtic), while values less than 3 indicate light tails (platykurtic).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERight-skewed with light tails\u003C/strong\u003E would have a positive skewness but kurtosis less than 3, which contradicts the given kurtosis value of 4.2. \u003Cstrong\u003ELeft-skewed with heavy tails\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eleft-skewed with light tails\u003C/strong\u003E would both require negative skewness values, but the given skewness is positive at +1.5. \u003Cstrong\u003ESymmetrical with heavy tails\u003C/strong\u003E would require a skewness value near zero, but the distribution clearly shows asymmetry with the positive skewness value.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERight-skewed distributions are common in medical data where there cannot be values below zero (like creatinine) and where there are occasional very high values pulling the mean above the median.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Skewness describes the asymmetry of a distribution relative to its mean, with positive skew indicating a longer right tail.","Kurtosis measures the heaviness of distribution tails, with higher values indicating more extreme outliers.","Normal distributions have a skewness of 0 and kurtosis of 3.","In medical data, right-skewed distributions are common for measurements that cannot be negative."],"references":["Motulsky H. Intuitive Biostatistics: A Nonmathematical Guide to Statistical Thinking. 4th ed. Oxford: Oxford University Press Academic US; 2017. Chapter 24; pg. 228","Sullivan LM. Essentials of biostatistics in public health. 3rd ed. Burlington (MA): Jones \u0026 Bartlett Learning; 2018.","Dawson B, Trapp RG. Basic \u0026 clinical biostatistics. 4th ed. New York: McGraw-Hill; 2004."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97233"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17478"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97233","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97233"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-23T10:12:56+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-23T10:12:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10168"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115224"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"upda